For each node u and state s, it iterates over the neighbors v. For each neighbor, it checks if the node v is the home of any of the friends without a car (p[i]). If so, it sets the corresponding bit in the state ns. Then, the code checks if dp[v][ns] is not set. If not, we need to add the new state. The missing code here is likely adding (v, ns) to the next queue (nq) and marking dp[v][ns] as true. So, the missing lines should be:
dp[v][ns] = true;
nq.push_back({v, ns}); This way, during BFS, each state transition is recorded, and the next level of nodes to process is built.
